<recipeml version="0.5">
  <recipe>
    <head>
      <title>Vodka Sauce</title>
      <categories>
        <cat>None</cat></categories>
      <yield>1</yield></head>
    <ingredients>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>pound</unit></amt>
        <item>Pasta (she recommends penne or ziti)</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>3</qty>
          <unit>tablespoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Unsalted butter</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>2/3</qty>
          <unit>cups</unit></amt>
        <item>Vodka</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1/4</qty>
          <unit>teaspoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Red pepper flakes</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>can</unit></amt>
        <item>Crushed tomatoes</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>3/4</qty>
          <unit>cups</unit></amt>
        <item>Heavy cream</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1/2</qty>
          <unit>teaspoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Salt</item></ing></ingredients>
    <directions>
      <step>  In answer to Mellisa, I had several Tomato, Cream and Vodka sauces on the
  old hard drive before the fall. Alas, this is all that remains and comes
  from my daughter at Georgetown University.
  
  Melt butter in a saute pan, and add vodka. Heat to bubbling, about 2
  minutes. Add red pepper, tomatoes, salt and heat through. Add cream and
  simmer gently for 10 minutes. Add cooked pasta to the pan and toss over low
  heat. Serve immediately. Serves 4. Posted to Kitmailbox Digest by
  CHICAGOAAA@aol.com on Mar 12, 1997
 
</step></directions></recipe></recipeml>
